#install.packages("tidyverse")
library(tidyverse)



# Define the start and end dates
start_date <- as.Date("2020-01-01")  # Replace with your desired start date
end_date <- as.Date("2020-03-11")    # Replace with your desired end date

# Convert the 'Date' column to the appropriate format
stock_returns$date <- as.Date(stock_returns$Date)

# Filter rows between the specified dates
filtered_stock_data <- stock_returns %>%
  filter(Date >= start_date, Date <= end_date)

stock_data_long <- filtered_stock_data %>%
  gather(key = "country", value = "cases", -1)
Warning: attributes are not identical across measure variables; they will be dropped
ggplot(stock_data_long , aes(x = as.Date(Date), y = cases, color = country)) +
  geom_line() +
  labs(x = "Date", y = "MSCI", title = "MSCI - Stock Market Indices") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

Plot the Model and Residuals

library(ggplot2)

# Plotting the regression result
ggplot(data = merge(log_returns, distance_measures, by.x = "Country", by.y = "country"), aes(x = distance_to_Wuhan, y = Log_Return)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "blue") +
  labs(x = "Distance to Wuhan", y = "Log Stock Market Return", title = "Regression Result")
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

# Plotting the residuals
residuals <- resid(model)
ggplot(data = data.frame(distance_to_Wuhan = merge(log_returns, distance_measures, by.x = "Country", by.y = "country")$distance_to_Wuhan, residuals = residuals), aes(x = distance_to_Wuhan, y = residuals)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed", color = "red") +
  labs(x = "Distance to Wuhan", y = "Residuals", title = "Residual Plot")

Total COVID-19 Cases as a Control Variable

This regression has the same event window with the first (main) regression. It is beacuse we need to check significance of the first regression.


start_date <- "2020-01-04" #first COVID-19 case in our dataset
end_date <- "2020-03-11" 

#take the difference of the total COVID-19 cases
total_case_diff = covid_cases_with_date_as_index[end_date,] - covid_cases_with_date_as_index[start_date,]

# Convert the column labels to a new column named "Column"
total_case_diff <- gather(total_case_diff, Country, Case_Difference, convert = TRUE)

# View the converted dataset
print(total_case_diff)

merged_dataset = merge(log_returns, distance_measures, total_case_diff, by.x = "Country", by.y = "country")
merged_dataset = merge(merged_dataset, total_case_diff, total_case_diff, by.x = "Country", by.y = "Country")

# Perform the regression
model <- lm(Log_Return ~ distance_to_Wuhan + Case_Difference, data = merged_dataset)

# View the summary of the regression model
summary(model)

Total Square COVID-19 Cases as a Control Variable

This part is not mentioned in the term paper!

This regression has the same event window with the first (main) regression. It is beacuse we need to check significance of the first regression.


start_date <- "2020-01-04" #first COVID-19 case in our dataset
end_date <- "2020-03-11" 

#take the difference of the total COVID-19 cases
total_case_diff = covid_cases_with_date_as_index[end_date,] - covid_cases_with_date_as_index[start_date,]

# Convert the column labels to a new column named "Column"
total_case_diff <- gather(total_case_diff, Country, Case_Difference, convert = TRUE)

# View the converted dataset
print(total_case_diff)

merged_dataset = merge(log_returns, distance_measures, total_case_diff, by.x = "Country", by.y = "country")
merged_dataset = merge(merged_dataset, total_case_diff, total_case_diff, by.x = "Country", by.y = "Country")

# Perform the regression
model <- lm(Log_Return ~ distance_to_Wuhan + Case_Difference +  I(Case_Difference^2), data = merged_dataset)

# View the summary of the regression model
summary(model)
